{"title":"Basic Data Types","markdown":{"headingText":"Basic Data Types","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-data-types","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**The Problem**\n\nYou import a participant's age from a form and try to calculate next year's age:\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nage <- \"34\"\nage_next_year <- age + 1\n```\n\n```\nError in age + 1 : non-numeric argument to binary operator\n```\n\nR refuses to do the math, even though `\"34\"` clearly looks like a number to you.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**Your Mission**\n\nUnderstand that R distinguishes between different fundamental *types* of data, and learn to check which type you're actually working with.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-think}\n**Think Before Coding**\n\n- Does `\"34\"` (with quotation marks) look different from `34` (without quotes) when you type it?\n- What other kinds of information, besides numbers, might a health dataset contain — names, yes/no answers, dates?\n:::\n\n## The R Concept\n\nEvery value in R has a **data type**, and R treats different types differently, even when they look similar to a human. The three you'll use constantly, starting today:\n\n- **Numeric** — actual numbers you can do math with: `34`, `22.8`, `-5`.\n- **Character** — text, always wrapped in quotes: `\"34\"`, `\"Female\"`, `\"Riverdale\"`. Note that `\"34\"` is text, *not* a number, purely because of the quotes.\n- **Logical** — `TRUE` or `FALSE` values (no quotes), used for yes/no conditions.\n\nYou can check any object's type with `class()`:\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nclass(34)      # numeric\nclass(\"34\")    # character\nclass(TRUE)    # logical\n```\n\nThe error at the top of this page happened because `age <- \"34\"` created a *character* object — text that happens to look like a number — and R correctly refuses to perform arithmetic on text.\n\n## Demonstration\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nclass(34)\n```\n\n```\n[1] \"numeric\"\n```\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nclass(\"34\")\n```\n\n```\n[1] \"character\"\n```\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nclass(TRUE)\n```\n\n```\n[1] \"logical\"\n```\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\n# The type mismatch that caused the original error\nage <- \"34\"\nclass(age)\n```\n\n```\n[1] \"character\"\n```\n\n## Explore\n\nRun `class(age + 1)` after setting `age <- \"34\"` and confirm you see the same error as in the opening problem. Then try `class(as.numeric(age) + 1)` — you're using a *conversion function* here, which you'll study properly on the numeric-data page next, but notice how wrapping `age` changes the outcome.\n\n## Solve the Problem\n\nThe fix is to make sure `age` is stored as a numeric value, not text:\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nage <- 34          # no quotes -> numeric\nclass(age)\n```\n\n```\n[1] \"numeric\"\n```\n\n```{r}\n#| eval: false\nage_next_year <- age + 1\nage_next_year\n```\n\n```\n[1] 35\n```\n\n## Interpret the Result\n\n`age_next_year` now correctly equals `35`, because `age` was stored as an actual number rather than a piece of text. The lesson generalizes: any time R refuses to do arithmetic you expect it to handle, `class()` is the first diagnostic tool to reach for.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mistake}\n**Common Mistakes**\n\n- **Adding quotes around numbers by habit.** `age <- \"34\"` looks harmless but silently creates text, not a number — a very common source of confusing downstream errors.\n- **Assuming R will \"figure out\" what you meant.** Unlike Excel, R does not automatically guess that `\"34\"` should behave like a number in a math context — it enforces the type strictly.\n- **Forgetting quotes around genuine text.** `sex <- Female` (no quotes) will error, because R interprets `Female` as an object name it can't find, not as the text `\"Female\"`.\n:::\n\n## Practice Problem\n\nFor each of the following, predict the result of `class()` before running it: `class(120)`, `class(\"120\")`, `class(FALSE)`, `class(\"TRUE\")`.\n\n## Challenge Problem\n\nA dataset column for blood type contains values like `\"O+\"`, `\"AB-\"`, `\"A+\"`. Explain, in your own words, why this column should be stored as character data rather than numeric, even though blood types are sometimes informally coded with numbers elsewhere.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Every R value has a type; the three fundamentals are numeric, character, and logical.\n- `class()` reveals an object's current type — your first stop when arithmetic or comparisons behave unexpectedly.\n- Quotes make the difference between a number (`34`) and text that merely looks like a number (`\"34\"`).\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-check}\n**Knowledge Check**\n\n1. **Multiple choice.** What is the class of `\"25\"` (with quotes)?\n   a) numeric\n   b) character\n   c) logical\n   d) integer\n\n2. **True or false.** R will automatically convert `\"25\"` to a number if you try to do math with it.\n\n3. **Find the error.**\n   ```r\n   n_visits <- \"4\"\n   total_visits <- n_visits + 2\n   ```\n\n4. **Predict the output.**\n   ```r\n   class(TRUE)\n   ```\n\n<details class=\"pbl-answer\">\n<summary>Show answers</summary>\n\n1. **b)** character — the quotes make it text, regardless of what it looks like.\n2. **False.** R will raise an error (`non-numeric argument to binary operator`) rather than silently converting it.\n3. `n_visits` is stored as character text (`\"4\"`), not a number, so `+ 2` fails. Fix: `n_visits <- 4` (no quotes).\n4. `[1] \"logical\"`\n\n</details>\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"